Here is a basic example of how you can create a modal dialog with custom content and button class in AngularJS:

```javascript
// Define the module
var app = angular.module('myApp', ['ui.bootstrap']);

// Define the controller
app.controller('myCtrl', function($scope, $uibModal) {
  $scope.open = function() {
    var modalInstance = $uibModal.open({
      templateUrl: 'myModalContent.html',
      controller: 'ModalInstanceCtrl',
      resolve: {
        items: function () {
          return $scope.items;
        }
      }
    });
  };
});

// Define the modal instance controller
app.controller('ModalInstanceCtrl', function ($scope, $uibModalInstance, items) {
  $scope.items = items;

  $scope.ok = function () {
    $uibModalInstance.close($scope.selected.item);
  };

  $scope.cancel = function () {
    $uibModalInstance.dismiss('cancel');
  };
});
```

In this example, we are using the `ui.bootstrap` module, which provides a set of UI components for AngularJS including modals.

In the `myCtrl` controller, we have a function `open` which opens a modal dialog. The template for this modal is defined in a separate HTML file (`myModalContent.html`).

In the `ModalInstanceCtrl` controller, we have two functions `ok` and `cancel` which are called when the user clicks the "OK" and "Cancel" buttons respectively.

The `myModalContent.html` file should look something like this:

```html
<div class="modal-header">
  <h3 class="modal-title">I'm a modal!</h3>
</div>
<div class="modal-body">
  <ul>
    <li ng-repeat="item in items">
      <a href="#" ng-click="selected.item = item">{{ item }}</a>
    </li>
  </ul>
</div>
<div class="modal-footer">
  <button class="btn btn-primary" ng-click="ok()">OK</button>
  <button class="btn btn-warning" ng-click="cancel()">Cancel</button>
</div>
```

This is a very basic example and you can customize the modal dialog to fit your needs.

