To toggle the prefix "not " in a label within a modal when a checkbox is clicked, you can use JavaScript to add an event listener to the checkbox. When the checkbox is clicked, the event listener will check the state of the checkbox and update the label accordingly.

Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```html
<!-- HTML structure -->
<div id="myModal" class="modal">
  <div class="modal-content">
    <input type="checkbox" id="toggleCheckbox">
    <label for="toggleCheckbox">not Label</label>
  </div>
</div>
```

```javascript
// JavaScript to toggle the prefix
document.getElementById('toggleCheckbox').addEventListener('change', function() {
  var label = document.querySelector('label[for="toggleCheckbox"]');
  if (this.checked) {
    label.textContent = 'not ' + label.textContent;
  } else {
    label.textContent = label.textContent.replace('not ', '');
  }
});
```

In this example:
- We have a modal with a checkbox and a label.
- The checkbox has an `id` of `toggleCheckbox`.
- The label is associated with the checkbox using the `for` attribute.
- We add an event listener to the checkbox that listens for the `change` event.
- When the checkbox is clicked, the event listener checks if the checkbox is checked.
- If the checkbox is checked, it prepends "not " to the label's text content.
- If the checkbox is unchecked, it removes "not " from the label's text content.

This way, the label's text content will toggle between "not Label" and "Label" depending on the state of the checkbox.

