Here is a simple jQuery snippet that handles a click event to process and display selected checkboxes for moving a repeating group of table columns:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
    // When a checkbox is clicked
    $('input[type="checkbox"]').click(function() {
        // Get the column index of the checkbox
        var columnIndex = $(this).closest('td').index();

        // Check if the checkbox is checked
        if ($(this).is(':checked')) {
            // If the checkbox is checked, move the column to the end of the table
            $(this).closest('tr').find('td').eq(columnIndex).appendTo($(this).closest('tr'));
        } else {
            // If the checkbox is unchecked, move the column to its original position
            $(this).closest('tr').find('td').eq(columnIndex).insertBefore($(this).closest('tr').find('td').eq(0));
        }
    });
});
```

This script works on a table where each row represents a different record and each column represents a different attribute of the record. It assumes that the first column contains checkboxes for selecting which columns to move. When a checkbox is clicked, it moves the corresponding column to the end of the table if the checkbox is checked, and moves it back to its original position if the checkbox is unchecked.

