function updateGradeTable(tableId, studentId, grade) {
    // Retrieve the table element
    var table = document.getElementById(tableId);

    // Find the row with the specified studentId
    var rows = table.getElementsByTagName('tr');
    for (var i = 0; i < rows.length; i++) {
        var cells = rows[i].getElementsByTagName('td');
        if (cells.length > 0 && cells[0].textContent === studentId) {
            // Update the grade cell in the same row
            cells[1].textContent = grade;
            return;
        }
    }

    // If the studentId is not found, add a new row
    var newRow = table.insertRow(rows.length);
    var cell1 = newRow.insertCell(0);
    var cell2 = newRow.insertCell(1);
    cell1.textContent = studentId;
    cell2.textContent = grade;

    // Optionally, if the grade is an image, set the cell's innerHTML
    if (grade.includes('<img')) {
        cell2.innerHTML = grade;
    }
}

// Example usage:
updateGradeTable('studentGrades', '101', 'A');
updateGradeTable('studentGrades', '102', '<img src="grade_a.png" alt="A" width="50" height="50">');
```

**Explanation**:
- The function `updateGradeTable` takes three parameters: `tableId` (the ID of the table), `studentId` (the ID of the student whose grade needs to be updated), and `grade` (the new grade to be set).
- It first retrieves the table element using `document.getElementById`.
- It then iterates over the rows of the table to find the row that contains the specified `studentId`.
- If the student is found, it updates the text content of the second cell in that row (which is assumed to be the grade cell) to the new `grade`.
- If the student is not found, it creates a new row at the end of the table and inserts the `studentId` and `grade` into the new cells.
- If the grade is provided as an HTML image tag, it sets the innerHTML of the grade cell to display the image instead of plain text.
- The function does not return any value.

