Here is a simple implementation of the function using JavaScript:

```javascript
function displayMessage(message, type, user) {
    let messageElement = document.createElement('div');
    messageElement.className = 'message';

    if (type === 'text') {
        messageElement.textContent = message;
    } else if (type === 'image') {
        let img = document.createElement('img');
        img.src = message;
        messageElement.appendChild(img);
    } else if (type === 'video') {
        let video = document.createElement('video');
        video.src = message;
        messageElement.appendChild(video);
    }

    if (user) {
        let userElement = document.createElement('span');
        userElement.className = 'user';
        userElement.textContent = '@' + user;
        messageElement.appendChild(userElement);
    }

    document.getElementById('chat').appendChild(messageElement);
}
```

In this function, we are creating a new `div` element for each message and setting its class to 'message'. Depending on the type of the message (text, image, or video), we are creating the appropriate HTML element (`div`, `img`, or `video`) and setting its `src` attribute to the message content.

If the message is a user mention, we are creating a new `span` element with class 'user' and setting its text content to '@' + the user name. We then append this `span` element to the message `div`.

Finally, we append the message `div` to the chat interface element with id 'chat'.

Please note that you need to have a HTML structure like this:

```html
<div id="chat"></div>
```

This function is very basic and does not handle all possible cases (like error handling, styling, etc.). It also assumes that the chat interface element exists and has the id 'chat'.

