Here is a simple example of how you can create an Alert factory in AngularJS:

```javascript
angular.module('myApp').factory('Alert', ['$modal', '$log', function ($modal, $log) {

  var alert = {};

  alert.show = function (options) {
    options = options || {};

    var modalInstance = $modal.open({
      templateUrl: 'alert.html',
      controller: 'AlertCtrl',
      resolve: {
        options: function () {
          return options;
        }
      }
    });

    modalInstance.result.then(function (selectedItem) {
      $log.info('Modal dismissed at: ' + new Date());
    }, function () {
      $log.info('Modal dismissed at: ' + new Date());
    });
  };

  return alert;
}]);

angular.module('myApp').controller('AlertCtrl', ['$scope', '$modalInstance', 'options', function ($scope, $modalInstance, options) {

  $scope.options = options;

  $scope.ok = function () {
    $modalInstance.close('OK');
  };

  $scope.cancel = function () {
    $modalInstance.dismiss('cancel');
  };
}]);
```

In this example, we have created a factory named 'Alert' that uses the '$modal' service to open a modal. The 'show' method of the 'Alert' factory takes an options object as a parameter, which allows you to customize the alert.

The 'AlertCtrl' controller is used to control the alert modal. It takes the 'options' object as a parameter and assigns it to the $scope.options variable. It also has two methods: 'ok' and 'cancel', which are used to close the modal.

To use this factory, you would simply call 'Alert.show' with an options object:

```javascript
Alert.show({
  title: 'Alert',
  message: 'This is an alert message',
  okText: 'OK',
  cancelText: 'Cancel'
});
```

You would also need to create an 'alert.html' template file that defines the layout of the alert modal.

