Here is a simple example of a React component that generates links for sharing content on social media and includes options for signing in, printing, and saving content:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const ShareAndSaveContent = ({ contentUrl }) => {
  const [isSignedIn, setIsSignedIn] = useState(false);

  const signIn = () => {
    setIsSignedIn(true);
    alert('Signed in successfully!');
  };

  const shareOnSocialMedia = (platform) => {
    let shareUrl = '';
    if (platform === 'facebook') {
      shareUrl = `https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=${contentUrl}`;
    } else if (platform === 'twitter') {
      shareUrl = `https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=${contentUrl}`;
    } else if (platform === 'linkedin') {
      shareUrl = `https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=${contentUrl}`;
    }
    window.open(shareUrl, '_blank');
  };

  const printContent = () => {
    window.print();
  };

  const saveContent = () => {
    const link = document.createElement('a');
    link.href = contentUrl;
    link.download = 'content.html';
    link.click();
  };

  return (
    <div>
      {isSignedIn ? (
        <button onClick={printContent}>Print</button>
      ) : (
        <button onClick={signIn}>Sign In</button>
      )}
      <button onClick={() => shareOnSocialMedia('facebook')}>Share on Facebook</button>
      <button onClick={() => shareOnSocialMedia('twitter')}>Share on Twitter</button>
      <button onClick={() => shareOnSocialMedia('linkedin')}>Share on LinkedIn</button>
      <button onClick={saveContent}>Save Content</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ShareAndSaveContent;
```

This component takes in a `contentUrl` prop which is the URL of the content you want to share or save. It has a state variable `isSignedIn` to keep track of whether the user is signed in or not. The `signIn` function sets the `isSignedIn` state to true and alerts the user that they have been signed in successfully. The `shareOnSocialMedia` function takes in a platform argument and opens a new window with the appropriate share URL for that platform. The `printContent` function calls the `window.print()` method to open the print dialog. The `saveContent` function creates a new link element, sets its `href` attribute to the `contentUrl`, sets its `download` attribute to 'content.html', and then clicks the link to download the content.

