Here's a simple example of a React component that displays matched lines from a repository with links to the source:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

class MatchedLines extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = {
      lines: []
    };
  }

  componentDidMount() {
    // Fetch the matched lines from the repository
    fetch('https://api.github.com/search/code?q=language:javascript+repo:username/repository')
      .then(response => response.json())
      .then(data => {
        this.setState({
          lines: data.items.map(item => {
            return {
              line: item.text_matches[0].fragment,
              link: item.html_url
            };
          })
        });
      });
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <h2>Matched Lines</h2>
        <ul>
          {this.state.lines.map((line, index) => (
            <li key={index}>
              <a href={line.link} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                {line.line}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    );
  }
}

export default MatchedLines;
```

This component fetches the matched lines from a GitHub repository using the GitHub API and displays them as a list of links. Each link points to the source line in the repository. The `componentDidMount` lifecycle method is used to fetch the data when the component mounts.

Please note that you need to replace `username/repository` with the actual username and repository name you want to search. Also, the GitHub API requires authentication for requests to private repositories, so you might need to add an access token to your request headers.

