Here is a simple example of a React component that generates a modal header with story details and optional backgrounds:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import PropTypes from 'prop-types';

const ModalHeader = ({ title, author, backgroundImage, onClose }) => {
  return (
    <div style={{ 
      backgroundImage: backgroundImage ? `url(${backgroundImage})` : 'none',
      backgroundSize: 'cover',
      backgroundPosition: 'center',
      padding: '1rem',
      color: 'white',
      display: 'flex',
      justifyContent: 'space-between',
      alignItems: 'center'
    }}>
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{author}</p>
      <button onClick={onClose}>Close</button>
    </div>
  );
}

ModalHeader.propTypes = {
  title: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
  author: PropTypes.string,
  backgroundImage: PropTypes.string,
  onClose: PropTypes.func.isRequired,
}

export default ModalHeader;
```

In this component, `title` and `author` are required props, `backgroundImage` and `onClose` are optional. The `onClose` prop is a function that should be called when the user wants to close the modal.

You can use this component in your React application like this:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import ModalHeader from './ModalHeader';

const App = () => {
  const [isModalOpen, setIsModalOpen] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setIsModalOpen(true)}>Open Modal</button>
      {isModalOpen && (
        <ModalHeader
          title="Story Title"
          author="Author Name"
          backgroundImage="https://example.com/background.jpg"
          onClose={() => setIsModalOpen(false)}
        />
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

In this example, the `ModalHeader` component is conditionally rendered when `isModalOpen` is true. When the user clicks the "Close" button, `isModalOpen` is set to false, which hides the modal.

